  "text": "Using systematic deletion analysis of an ime1-lacZ fusion we demonstrate that the transcription of IME1 is regulated by a remarkably large region, over 2,100 bp long, which is the largest region known in S. cerevisiae. In comparison, the HO gene, another gene with a long and complex promoter, is made of only 1,400 bp [CITATION_1] . Preliminary data suggest that 5Ј of the 2,100-bp upstream region of IME1 there are yet additional elements that control its transcription: Granot et al. [CITATION_2] showed that multiple copies of an 0.5-kb XhoI-BglII fragment from positions Ϫ3166 to Ϫ3762 of IME1 promote low levels of sporulation to a MATa/MATa diploid. They proposed that a titration of a negative regulator that binds to this region is responsible for derepression of the transcription of IME1 in this mater diploid [CITATION_3] . In agreement, in this report we demonstrate that deletion of this region promotes a twofold increase in the expression of ime1-lacZ in MATa/MATa diploids ( Fig. 1 column B , compare YCpAS128 and YCpAS134).",
